103. Play upon Words, etc. In the same connection men- tion may be made of the fondness which Cicero and some of his correspondents show for playing upon words in their familiar letters Illustrations are tu istic to Hateriano iure [jurisprudence] delectas, ego me ln'c Hirtiano [iura ‘sauce ’] (Fam. 9. 18. 3) ; tu, qni ceteris caaerc didicisti, in Britannia ne ab essedariis decipiaris caveto, ‘you who have learned how to draw up securities for others, look out for your own security -and don't be taken in by the essedarii' (Fam. 7. 6. 2). Cicero’s letters tobis legal friend Trebatius (Fam. Bk. 7) are full of legal puns. Other good instances of similar witti- cisms are to be found in An. 1.16. 10 and in the letters to Paetus (Fam. Bk. 9). Cf. also notes to honoris cansa, Epist. XIX. 2, and occidione occisum, XXXIV. 7. Cicero had a great reputation for wit of this sort (cf. Fam. 9. 16. 4), and after his death his secretary Tiro edited his witty say- ings. Cf. Quint. 6. 3. 5 ; Macrob. Sat. 2. 1. 12.
